  "prompt": "Why India isn't getting a permanent seat in UNSC?",
  "response": "India's quest for a permanent seat in the UN Security Council (UNSC) has been challenging due to several key reasons:\n\n1. Existing Permanent Members' Opposition\n- Current P5 members (US, UK, Russia, China, France) are reluctant to expand the Security Council\n- Some members, particularly China, have explicitly opposed India's candidature\n\n2. Geopolitical Dynamics\n- China has historically blocked India's bid to protect its strategic interests\n- Complex regional power dynamics and rivalries\n\n3. Structural Challenges\n- Reforming UN Security Council requires consensus among existing members\n- No clear mechanism for expanding permanent membership\n\n4. Competing Candidates\n- Multiple countries like Brazil, Germany, Japan, and others also seek permanent seats\n- Lack of unified support for a single candidate or expansion formula\n\n5. Historical Background\n- Original UNSC structure reflects post-World War II power dynamics\n- Reluctance to significantly alter established geopolitical representation\n\n6. Reform Efforts\n- India is part of G4 nations (Brazil, Germany, Japan, India) advocating for UNSC reforms\n- Continues diplomatic efforts through multilateral platforms\n\nDespite these challenges, India remains a strong candidate due to:\n- Large democratic population\n- Significant economic and military potential\n- Growing global diplomatic influence\n\nIndia continues to lobby for UNSC permanent membership through diplomatic negotiations and international partnerships.",
